liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Three Australian government-assisted flights have left Tel Aviv for Dubai. They include two RAAF planes and one privately contracted flight. Foreign Minister Penny Wong said 1,200 Australians have been assisted with requests to leave Israel. "We did have many people who were registered for the flights who indicated they intended to fly, but at the last minute did not wish to," she said. Ms Wong said another flight out of the embattled region would likely leave today Israeli time. "People should consider that may be our last flight for the foreseeable future. I've been saying for some days ... that if people wish to leave they should take the first available option, they should not wait for another option."

items.synopsis: Follow our live updates on the fallout from the Voice to Parliament referendum's defeat on Monday, October 16, 2023.

title.children: Indigenous people urged to stay resilient, 'keep fighting the fight'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Charmayne Allison Maxine Carlton says she's worried about her grandson's future, now the Voice has been voted down. The Warlpiri woman is president of Anthelk-Ewlpaye (Charles Creek) town camp, on the outskirts of Alice Springs. Aboriginal communities like hers are some of the poorest and most disadvantaged in the country. She said on the night of the referendum, she turned off the tv and "walked away", because it was too difficult to watch. "I was devastated. It was very hurtful. Not only hurtful … heartful. Real ache," she said, placing her hand on her chest. "You know, where to now for us?" She had hoped the Voice would bring change for her community. "What's going to happen to the future of my son and my grandson?" she said. "Are they still going to be living in these same top-down approach policies and government regulations, government rules?" She said Indigenous people now needed to "buckle up together and make a way forward". "They say that we're resilient people," she said. "I think we're going to keep on tracking, keep fighting the fight."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Warlpiri woman urges to 'keep fighting the fight'

Reporting by Charmayne Allison
Maxine Carlton says she's worried about her grandson's future, now the Voice has been voted down.
The Warlpiri woman is president of Anthelk-Ewlpaye (Charles Creek) town camp, on the outskirts of Alice Springs.
Aboriginal communities like hers are some of the poorest and most disadvantaged in the country.
She said on the night of the referendum, she turned off the tv and "walked away", because it was too difficult to watch.
"I was devastated. It was very hurtful. Not only hurtful … heartful. Real ache," she said, placing her hand on her chest.
"You know, where to now for us?"
She had hoped the Voice would bring change for her community.
"What's going to happen to the future of my son and my grandson?" she said.
"Are they still going to be living in these same top-down approach policies and government regulations, government rules?"
She said Indigenous people now needed to "buckle up together and make a way forward".
"They say that we're resilient people," she said.
"I think we're going to keep on tracking, keep fighting the fight."
